\caption{
\textbf{Building and training evidential models.} \textbf{(A)} Evidential layers can be added to the end of exisiting molecular feature extractor neural networks. The output of the evidential layer is the parameters ($\bm{m}$) defining the molecule's evidential distribution. \textbf{(B)} For continuous regression learning problems, the evidential distribution $p(\bm{\theta}|\bm{m})$ can take the form of a Normal-Inverse-Gamma distribution, where $\bm{m} = \{\gamma, \upsilon, \alpha, \beta\}$, to yield both property prediction and uncertainty estimates. Color represents likelihood density (darker $=$ greater density). \textbf{(C)} The model (feature extractor and evidential layer) is trained end-to-end using backpropagation with a dual-objective loss that jointly maximizes model fit and inflates uncertainty (i.e., minimizes evidence) on errors.}
