Using this smaller but public dataset, we compare MIST first on the task of fingerprint prediction to variants of MIST that do not include pairwise neutral loss featurization (``MIST - pairwise"), use no auxiliary substructure losses (``MIST - MAGMa"), do not train on simulated fingerprints (``MIST - simulated") or use only a feed forward neural network (``FFN"). We make predictions for 4096-bit circular Morgan fingerprints, which are straightforward to generate using RDKit ~\cite{landrum_rdkit_2013}. %


As with the larger proprietary dataset, MIST sharply outperforms the FFN model in terms of cosine similarity and log likelihood (Fig. \ref{fig:ablation}a,b; Tab. \ref{tab:sup-fp-ablation}). Interestingly, we find that outside of using the overall chemical formula transformer, fingerprint unfolding has the largest effect on the performance of cosine similarity. We further validate that this effect is due to the addition of the unfolding loss rather than additional model parameters (Section \ref{supp_unfolding}). Unlike in the case of CSI:FingerID fingerprint bit predictions, pairwise embeddings do not appear to improve performance of MIST, which may be a function of the limited public benchmarking dataset size. Upon an additional exploration to probe the effect of pairwise features with the full proprietary dataset, we find pairwise features to be neutral-to-beneficial in the full dataset, justifying their inclusion in the full model (Tab. \ref{tab:sup-fp-pairwise-csi}). In further support of dataset limitations, we find that cosine similarity seems to be improving linearly as a function of dataset size in this regime on both the public dataset (Fig. \ref{fig:ablation}c) and the full, partially proprietary dataset (Fig. \ref{fig:SI-csi-ablation}a). Log likelihood based evaluations showcase similar but noisier trends, as expected because the model is not explicitly trained to maximize log likelihood (Fig. \ref{fig:ablation}d, \ref{fig:SI-csi-ablation}b). While we conduct a smaller set of ablations for various intensity representation strategies (Tab. \ref{tab:sup-fp-inten-ablation}), we are unable to find a representation that outperforms a simple concatenation of floating point intensities to the model hidden representations. This is one potential avenue for future work to improve upon model performance.

In addition to the feed forward network baseline, we also compare MIST to an internal reimplementation of a sinusoidal embeddings transformer \cite{neuvoronov_multiscale_2022}, which we find to perform equivalently to the feed forward network on this data regime. Given that sinusoidal transformers for mass spectrometry are being contemporaneously developed and potential deviations in implementation, we relegate further details on this comparison to the Supplementary Information (Section \ref{supp_transformer_baseline}).

Ablations measuring retrieval accuracy further support the utility of a contrastive-fingerprint hybrid retrieval distance. Retrieval accuracies are computed for various ``top-$k$" values using different retrieval scoring functions including the full MIST contrastive function (``MIST contrastive + fingerprint"), only contrastive distance (``MIST contrastive"), only fingerprint distance (``MIST fingerprint"), contrastive distance computed with a model that was not pretrained on fingerprint distance (``MIST contrastive - pretrain"), contrastive distances for a feed forward network (``FFN contrastive") and fingerprints computed with a FFN model (``FFN fingerprint"). The full MIST retrieval using a weighted average of contrastive and fingerprint distances performs better than either distance alone at 30.7\% Top 1 accuracy and 75.7\% Top-20 accuracy (Fig. \ref{fig:ablation}e, Tab. \ref{tab:sup-retrieval-ablation}). Curiously, when using Morgan fingerprints, contrastive and fingerprint retrieval accuracies when computed independently are near equivalent unlike the proprietary dataset case. This reaffirms that the choice of fingerprint may add additional biases to retrieval. Excitingly, we observe that MIST architecture Top-1\% accuracy improves steadily as we increase the amount of training data (Fig. \ref{fig:ablation}f), indicating that MIST should scale well as additional labeled data becomes available, a key benefit of such neural network approaches.

