Acquiring and screening a large number of diverse substrates is the most salient challenge that tends to limit the number of distinct components used in HTE campaigns, which often leverage the combinatorial nature of discrete variable selection. For example, the C--N coupling dataset from Ahneman et al. \cite{ahneman_predicting_2018} covers 4140 reactions defined by the combination of 15 choices for the aryl halide, 23 additives, 4 Pd catalysts, 3 bases, 1 amine, and 1 solvent, at fixed time, temperature, and concentrations. Similarly, Perera et al.’s dataset of 5760 Suzuki reactions \cite{perera_platform_2018} was defined by combinations of 5 electrophiles, 6 nucleophiles, 11 ligands, 7 bases, and 4 solvents. Even a few choices for each component can quickly represent a large experimental space, for which there tends to be a higher cost associated with the HTE campaigns and, particularly with significant numbers of distinct products, a higher analytical burden.

The variation of individual components or aspects of reaction conditions is directly tied to the applicability domain, as a model should not be expected to generalize
to a new molecule or input that is too dissimilar from what it has been trained on. As an extreme example, a model that has only seen reactions performed at room temperature cannot understand the influence of temperature on reaction outcome. In the Ahneman et al. study \cite{ahneman_predicting_2018}, the component with the greatest variation in the dataset was the additive species, with 23 total choices, which justifies the evaluation of model generalization to unseen additives in the original paper. With only three bases explored, it is unrealistic to expect the model to anticipate the performance of a fourth unseen base. At the same time, a model trained on a narrow subset of reaction space in general cannot be expected to generalize well to other areas of that space, making it vital to select an appropriate set of representative examples.

Mathematically, extrapolation is generally thought of as data that falls outside of the convex hull of training data; however, high-dimensional datasets almost always represent extrapolative tasks by this definition.\cite{balestriero_learning_2021} The notion of similarity between training and testing points and what comprises extrapolation in a chemical sense has no strict definition, but distance in chemical feature space (e.g., using descriptors or molecular/reaction fingerprints) is a natural approach. Structural similarity has been used to estimate the domain of applicability and uncertainty of predictive models.\cite{toplak_assessment_2014, rakhimbekova_comprehensive_2020}

\section{Selecting a reaction performance metric as an output variable}

There are many commonly-reported reaction performance metrics that can be used as the prediction target (output variable) in data-driven models. The two most common are yield, bounded between 0 and 100, and selectivity (e.g., enantiomeric ratio, regioselectivity, etc), which is a continuous scalar metric. Other metrics such as reaction rate or rate constants are less common \cite{lu_broadly_2022,haas_predicting_2022} but of high interest to process chemists in particular. Rate is a time and resource-intensive measurement to collect, requiring yields/conversions at many timepoints, but can be reliably assayed across orders of magnitude and provides insight for practical experimental considerations such as reaction concentration, temperature, and time. Enantioselectivity as reflected by $\Delta \Delta G^\ddagger$ is a compelling choice for an output variable and has been used in a significant number of successful workflows \cite{crawford_data_2021,sigman_development_2016,reid_holistic_2019}: it is a scalar metric that is centered at 0 when unselective, and due to the relative precision of measuring enantiomeric ratio (e.r.), does not tend to have a long-tailed distribution. Further, {e.r.} most often corresponds to the difference between enantio-determining transition states with the general reaction mechanism otherwise being the same, allowing one to neglect factors that confound modeling yield as an output, such as side reactions or differences in turnover rates of a catalyst. Likewise, regioselectivity is an internally-consistent metric that relies only on direct comparisons between candidate atom sites \cite{guan_regio-selectivity_2021,guan_snar_2023,nippa_enabling_2022,caldeweyher_hybrid_2023}. 

While selectivity is a useful metric for a subset of reactions, the more universal and widely reported metric in synthetic organic chemistry is yield. Generally, yield prediction has only been successful within large, high-throughput datasets in single/narrow reaction classes. Similar attempts to model diverse literature or “real-world” electronic laboratory notebook (ELN) data produce poorer results given the abundance of confounding variables (e.g., concentrations, time, scale, experimental hardware, experimentalist) that may be unaccounted for in the reaction description \cite{saebi_use_2023,schwaller_prediction_2021}. Different data sources tend to exhibit different distributions of reported reaction yields (Figure \ref{fig:datasets}B). 

Yield is a particularly challenging target to predict. It quantifies the efficiency of several successive microscopic steps and is implicitly affected by changes in reaction conditions that may prompt different mechanistic pathways. It is an inherently noisier value that may include issues related to isolation of the product, which challenges modeling efforts as the reported yield incorporates both reactivity and purification.
Importantly, this is also a time-dependent process wherein the relative yields across conditions are sensitive to the choice of when the reaction is assayed. For example, the ability to distinguish the efficacy of two catalysts (one fast, one slow) can be lost if the reactions are performed on long time scales. Most datasets are acquired using a single time point without regard for the rate-dependence of yield; further, researchers may intentionally choose longer reaction times to achieve higher yields, not realizing that this might be obfuscating differences in reaction rate.

Reported yields can also be of several types—isolated, assay, or even LCAP (liquid chromatography area percent), just to name a few—further increasing modeling complexity (Figure \ref{fig:yield}). Selectivity can suffer from the same ambiguity, but is more consistently assayed without isolation. LCAP is a common output from HTE campaigns where it is unrealistic to calibrate yields using product standards for every example. The well-defined range of yield values (0-100\%) additionally presents a modeling complication, as many architectures from linear regression to neural networks are able to make predictions outside of this physical range. Compressing or truncating predictions using techniques like logistic regression or sigmoid activation functions does not tend to improve modeling in our experience. Simplifying the task to a binary (0\% versus $>$0\% yield) or categorical (binned yield intervals) classification rather than a regression lowers the analytical burden for data acquisition and mitigates the impact of noise, but still does not guarantee the ability to train a useful model.

