While there are hundreds of publications developing and evaluating these methods on computational benchmarks (e.g., \cite{brown_guacamol:_2018}), experimental validations of deep generative model predictions are rare. A few exceptions are worth noting. \citeauthor{polykovskiy_entangled_2018} used a generative model to propose 300,000 molecules as potential JAK3 kinase inhibitors, which were filtered to 5000 using docking, clustering, and medchem filters, filtered again to 100 using molecular dynamics simulations, and finally \emph{one} molecule was hand selected and validated \cite{polykovskiy_entangled_2018}. A second study from the same company filtered 30,000 generated structures down to 40, then selected six to test on the basis of synthesizability \cite{zhavoronkov_deep_2019}. In an application to materials discovery, \citeauthor{sumita_hunting_2018} used RL-based generation and DFT calculations to propose 3200 molecules with targeted maximum absorption wavelengths, of which 86 passed DFT evaluation and six with known synthetic routes were synthesized \cite{sumita_hunting_2018}.





